In this context it depends what you mean with an extremely large input. On modern computers, bubble sort will execute very fast, also for relatively large inputs. My suspicion is that the function executes too fast relative to your duration resolution (microseconds). 

My advice would be not to cast the duration that is calculated by the clock, but to store it directly, something along the following lines (untested):

    struct analysis {
      analysis(const char* x, const chrono::nanoseconds y) : func_name{x}, calc_time{y} {}
  
      string func_name;
      chrono::nanoseconds calc_time;
    };

    void Utility::tEnd(const char* func_name) {
      std::chrono::nanoseconds elapsed{chrono::high_resolution_clock::now() - sink};    
      time_coll.emplace_back(func_name, elapsed);    
    }

Then, when reporting the elapsed time, convert to microseconds at that time:

    void Utility::pStat() {
      using FractionalUs = std::chrono::duration&lt;double, std::micro&gt;;
      for (const auto&amp; elem: time_coll) {
        cout &lt;&lt; elem.func_name  &lt;&lt; &quot; : &quot; 
             &lt;&lt; std::chrono::duration_cast&lt;FractionalUs&gt;(elem.calc_time).count() &lt;&lt; &quot;us\n&quot;;
      }
    }

